MEDIUM|reconcile/bipartite.go:198|bipartiteGroups accepts a candidate into a group when mergeable() holds for ANY current member (single-linkage OR over groups[r]), so for 3+ distinct sources a transitive chain still over-merges non-duplicate endpoints. Example: sources A,B,C each with one finding where sim(a,b)=0.75 and sim(b,c)=0.75 (both >=0.7 merge) but sim(a,c)=0.2: A seeds {a}; b merges to {a,b}; c is accepted via mergeable(b,c) -> {a,b,c}, merging a and c which are NOT duplicates. The 1:1 constraint only caps one finding per source per group; it does not prevent cross-source single-linkage chaining, contradicting the structural-fix claim in the file header (bipartite.go:8-16). The AC2 benchmark does not cover the all-pairwise-mergeable-except-endpoints case (its transitive test uses a GRAY bridge, not two merge-strength links).|In bipartiteGroups acceptance loop (bipartite.go:196-205) switch from ANY-member to complete-linkage: require mergeable(member, candidate) for ALL current members (set accept=true, then break to false on the first non-mergeable member) OR require the group's MAX distance to the candidate to be at/below the merge cutoff. Add a 3-source fixture (sim a-b=0.75, b-c=0.75, a-c=0.2) asserting a and c land in separate groups. Re-run the AC2 suite to confirm no regression.|correctness|120|reconcile/bipartite.go:182-208|claude
MEDIUM|reconcile/bipartite.go:104|hungarianAssign always pads to a max(rows,cols) square and runs full O(n^3) Kuhn-Munkres even when one dimension is 1. bipartiteGroups calls it once per source; for unattributed findings the anon srcKey scheme (dedupe.go:85-92) makes every finding its own source, so S=n single-candidate sources and the per-step square grows 1..n -> overall O(n^4) (plus O(n^3) for the square fills). DedupeCluster (the public API, dedupe.go:40) passes empty reviewers, so a large single-location/AST cluster of unattributed findings hits this directly. The O(V^3) technical constraint assumes V small per cluster, but grouper.go notes keyed AST clusters are unbounded.|Short-circuit hungarianAssign when rows==1 or cols==1 to an O(rows) / O(cols) argmin instead of building and solving a padded square (bipartite.go:104-134). Optionally cap V per location cluster. Add a benchmark on a ~500-finding unattributed single-location cluster and assert runtime does not scale ~n^4.|performance|120|reconcile/bipartite.go:104-134|claude
MEDIUM|reconcile/dedupe.go:209|In the DBSCAN noise block each isolated singleton gets id AmbiguousID(File,Line,Problem,Problem). Two findings from the SAME source at the same file/line with identical PROBLEM text are not cross-source neighbors (denseNeighbor false for equal srcKey), so each is its own solo group and, when any unrelated cross-source dense pair also exists in the cluster (dense==true), BOTH are emitted as noise singletons with byte-identical ids (inputs are equal, not merely hash-colliding). ambiguous.go:30-33 calls aliasing two distinct sidecar entries to one id 'the one outcome the design forbids', and a host adjudicating by id cannot distinguish the two entries.|Disambiguate singleton noise ids by folding the finding's source key or cluster index into the AmbiguousID inputs (dedupe.go:205-213), or assert uniqueness of emitted ids before return. Add a test: cluster of two identical same-source findings plus one cross-source dense pair; assert the two noise entries have distinct ids.|correctness|30|reconcile/dedupe.go:199-214|claude
MEDIUM|reconcile/dedupe.go:195|The DBSCAN density predicate denseNeighbor = mergeable(a,b) && srcKeys[a]!=srcKeys[b] is meant to enforce 'density needs two DISTINCT sources, not one source repeating itself' (dedupe.go:186-188). But srcKeys gives every empty-Reviewer finding a UNIQUE per-finding anon key (dedupe.go:85-92), so two unattributed findings always count as cross-source. Two unattributed copies of the same hallucination therefore corroborate each other into a dense cluster and neither is isolated -- a true hallucination is kept, the failure AC3 exists to prevent. The attributed reviewer-pool pipeline (Reconcile with named sources) is unaffected; only unattributed input (e.g. DedupeCluster public API) hits this.|For the density predicate specifically, treat all unattributed findings as a single non-corroborating source (or require corroboration from a named distinct source), while keeping the per-finding unique key for the bipartite matching path that needs it. Add a test with two empty-Reviewer identical findings asserting they do not corroborate into a dense cluster.|correctness|60|reconcile/dedupe.go:79-92,186-196|claude
LOW|reconcile/dedupe.go:124|The gray-pair scan classifies pairs purely on token Jaccard via classify(tokens[i],tokens[j]) and ignores the AST GroupKey, whereas mergeable(), denseNeighbor, and bipartite acceptance all treat a shared non-empty AST key as authoritative duplicate evidence. Two same-source AST-isomorphic findings (which bipartite cannot merge because they share a source, so they land in different groups) are then judged by tokens alone and can be wrongly recorded as a gray pair despite being structurally identical per the 13.1 signal the rest of the file trusts.|Short-circuit the gray scan when keys[i] != \"\" && keys[i] == keys[j] (treat as merge-equivalent, skip gray recording) so the AST signal is honored consistently (dedupe.go:119-132). Add a test with two same-source findings sharing a GroupKey but divergent tokens asserting no gray entry is recorded.|maintainability|15|reconcile/dedupe.go:119-132|claude
LOW|reconcile/reconcile.go:106|Summary has no field for ambiguous/noise counts. Findings isolated as DBSCAN noise are removed from merged (so excluded from TotalFindings=len(merged) at reconcile.go:116) and from ClustersCollapsed/SeverityDisagreements, appearing only in Result.Ambiguous. A reader of the summary alone cannot reconcile PerSourceCounts (input) against output+sidecar totals -- a transparency/audit gap for an isolation feature whose business goal (epic Success Criteria) is to let the sidecar be trusted as strictly uncorroborated noise.|Add AmbiguousCount / NoiseCount (and optionally a gray-vs-noise breakdown) fields to Summary (reconcile.go:37-60) and populate from len(ambiguous) and the noise subset in Reconcile. Add an invariant test: sum of input findings == expanded output records + ambiguous entries accounted for.|maintainability|30|reconcile/reconcile.go:95-119|claude
LOW|reconcile/dbscan.go:65|dbscanLabels grows the seed FIFO via seeds = append(seeds, qn...) on every core-point expansion, appending the full neighbor list including already-queued/labeled points (deduped only later by the label check). On a large single-location AST cluster (grouper.go notes keyed clusters are unbounded) seeds can grow to O(E)=O(n^2) with repeated entries -- needless memory and extra loop passes. Correctness is unaffected (label checks make re-pops idempotent).|Track a queued []bool (or reuse label state) and append only unvisited, not-yet-queued neighbors when expanding a core point (dbscan.go:60-66). Verify labels are unchanged on existing fixtures and seeds length stays O(n).|performance|30|reconcile/dbscan.go:53-67|claude
LOW|reconcile/bipartite.go:8|The bipartite.go header and bipartiteGroups docstring describe 'optimal assignment' for N-way matching, but the N-way result is an incremental pairwise greedy reduction in sorted-source order: only each pairwise step is optimal, and a candidate matched early can lock a group a later better-fitting candidate is then excluded from by the 1:1 constraint. The epic clarifications already acknowledge ordering sensitivity (bounded for N<=5), so this is a documentation-accuracy gap rather than a logic bug -- the 'optimal' wording overstates the global guarantee.|Reword the header (bipartite.go:8-16) and bipartiteGroups docstring to 'greedy incremental pairwise (each step optimal; N-way result order-dependent, bounded for small N)'. Optionally add a test demonstrating order sensitivity so the limitation is documented rather than implied-away.|maintainability|30|reconcile/bipartite.go:1-16,136-171|claude
LOW|reconcile/dedupe.go:59|dedupeCluster documents that keys must be the same length as cluster but never validates it. mergeable (dedupe.go:99) and the distance build (dedupe.go:74) index keys[i]/keys[j]; a caller passing a shorter slice panics with index-out-of-range deep inside matching rather than failing clearly at the boundary. Internal callers (clusterKeys, DedupeCluster) always pass an aligned slice, so this is a defensive/robustness gap for external embedders of the public package.|Add an early guard in dedupeCluster (dedupe.go:60): if len(keys) != n, panic with a descriptive message (or pad/return an error per the package's error convention). Add a unit test passing mismatched lengths.|error-handling|15|reconcile/dedupe.go:59-104|claude
LOW|reconcile/dedupe.go:250|classify returns relMerge,1.0 when BOTH token sets are empty, so mergeable treats two findings with empty/whitespace-only PROBLEM text as distance-0 duplicates that will merge (subject to the one-per-source cap). Empty problem text is more plausibly 'no signal' than 'identical issue'; the current behavior silently collapses unrelated empties. The code comment documents this as intentional, so confirm the intent before changing.|If empties should not merge, return relDistinct,0.0 for the both-empty case (dedupe.go:249-251) or require a non-empty token set for relMerge. Add a test with two findings whose Problem is only punctuation/whitespace asserting they do not merge. If intentional, add an explicit test pinning the merge behavior.|correctness|15|reconcile/dedupe.go:249-255|claude

